latestPosts.caption:
as a curve model it’s incredibly easy to tie your self worth to how the industry is going (and it’s not looking great for us plus/curve girls!). I have to constantly remind myself that change only happens if we continue to be the representation that’s needed in the industry, and that we aren’t going away. 

It’s easy to want to lose the weight to fit the mold that’s getting casted right now (to be honest I booked more when I weighed less) but we have to stand firm so the industry (and by proxy, society) will bend to us. There has always and will always be plus sized people and we deserve to be represented in the media we see. 

Over a holiday at home one of my family members asked me “are you going to lose weight to fit into the current trend of the industry?” (not a pointed question, we were having a frank discussion of how things were looking) and I replied “no, it’ll come back around”. Which, of course it will, but why should we have to wait for that to happen? Bodies should not be some cyclical trend that you get match for a couple years at a time, representation should be a given.

I can’t promise my weight won’t fluctuate, but I do promise that in me you will never see me losing weight to fit whatever mold society haphazardly thrusts upon us. 

My curves are here to stay and we are beautiful regardless of what is trending♡

Corset from @selkie (not an ad, but Selkie is truly a pioneer in representation of ALL and I hold them dear to my heart. When I shot with them, it was the first set my body diversity truly felt celebrated and wasn’t there as a “here, damn!” diversity moment)

Garnet necklace from @artbyjacstudio the only person I buy crystals from <3
